  <title translate="true">Moment of Inertia</title>
  <keywords>
    <keyword translate="true">Moment of Inertia</keyword>
  </keywords>
  <body>
    <para styleclass="Normal"><table styleclass="PopupTable" rowcount="1" colcount="1" style="width:490px;">
      <tr style="vertical-align:top">
        <td style="height:37px;">
          <para styleclass="Normal"><text styleclass="Normal" style="font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold; font-style:italic;" translate="true">Moment of inertia</text><text styleclass="Normal" style="font-size:10pt;" translate="true"> is the mass property of a rigid body that determines the torque needed for a desired angular acceleration about an axis of rotation. </text><text styleclass="Normal" style="font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold; font-style:italic;" translate="true">Moment of inertia</text><text styleclass="Normal" style="font-size:10pt;" translate="true"> depends on the shape of the body and may be different around different axes of rotation.</text></para>
          <para styleclass="Normal"><text styleclass="Normal" style="font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold;" translate="true">Mech</text><text styleclass="Normal" style="font-size:10pt; font-style:italic;" translate="true">Designer</text><text styleclass="Normal" style="font-size:10pt;" translate="true"> calculates the Moment of Inertia at the center of Gravity. We use the Parallel Axis Theorem to refer the Inertia to different points.</text></para>
        </td>
      </tr>
    </table></para>
